1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,854
In the previous episode, I explored why
Articulate exists.

2
00:00:03,854 --> 00:00:08,104
This time, I want to answer what should be
a

3
00:00:08,104 --> 00:00:09,621
much simpler question.

4
00:00:09,621 --> 00:00:11,492
What exactly is Articulate?

5
00:00:11,492 --> 00:00:16,535
The problem is that the answer has changed
quite a few times.

6
00:00:16,535 --> 00:00:20,786
At different points, Articulate has been a
documentation tool, a

7
00:00:20,786 --> 00:00:25,036
knowledge graph, a conversational
assistant, a discovery platform and an

8
00:00:25,036 --> 00:00:26,554
architecture modelling tool.

9
00:00:26,554 --> 00:00:29,614
Each idea solved part of the problem.

10
00:00:29,614 --> 00:00:33,468
But none of them really captured the
bigger picture.

11
00:00:33,468 --> 00:00:37,718
Today, I see Articulate as an exploration
into something I

12
00:00:37,718 --> 00:00:39,235
call architectural intelligence.

13
00:00:39,235 --> 00:00:43,486
But to explain what I mean by that, I
first

14
00:00:43,486 --> 00:00:46,149
need to talk about architectural
knowledge.

15
00:00:46,149 --> 00:00:49,272
Most architecture tools are built around
artefacts.

16
00:00:49,272 --> 00:00:52,800
We create documents, diagrams, decision
records and models.

17
00:00:52,800 --> 00:00:55,518
All of those things are useful.

18
00:00:55,518 --> 00:00:59,451
But each one only represents part of the
architecture.

19
00:00:59,451 --> 00:01:03,789
The architecture itself is much more than
any individual artefact.

20
00:01:03,789 --> 00:01:06,102
It includes facts and assumptions.

21
00:01:06,102 --> 00:01:07,651
Evidence and decisions.

22
00:01:07,651 --> 00:01:09,559
Capabilities, constraints and
relationships.

23
00:01:09,559 --> 00:01:13,897
It includes why decisions were made, what
alternatives were considered

24
00:01:13,897 --> 00:01:17,425
and how the architecture has changed over
time.

25
00:01:17,425 --> 00:01:21,762
Together, all of this forms a body of
architectural knowledge.

26
00:01:21,762 --> 00:01:26,100
And unlike a document, that knowledge
never really stops changing.

27
00:01:26,100 --> 00:01:30,438
So one of the central ideas behind
Articulate is to

28
00:01:30,438 --> 00:01:33,966
treat that architectural knowledge as the
primary asset.

29
00:01:33,966 --> 00:01:36,684
Documents, diagrams and models still
exist.

30
00:01:36,684 --> 00:01:41,021
But instead of being isolated sources of
information, they contribute

31
00:01:41,021 --> 00:01:44,549
to a continuously evolving understanding
of the architecture.

32
00:01:44,549 --> 00:01:48,705
This is where AI starts to become
interesting.

33
00:01:48,705 --> 00:01:53,814
Articulate is designed from the outset as
an AI-native system.

34
00:01:53,814 --> 00:01:57,969
But that does not mean replacing the
architect.

35
00:01:57,969 --> 00:02:04,032
The architect still owns the decisions,
the judgement and ultimately the
accountability.

36
00:02:04,032 --> 00:02:07,234
I see AI as a collaborator.

37
00:02:07,234 --> 00:02:12,343
It can help discover information, identify
inconsistencies and challenge assumptions.

38
00:02:12,343 --> 00:02:17,452
It can help explain relationships, reason
about change and surface

39
00:02:17,452 --> 00:02:21,608
information that might otherwise be
difficult to find.

40
00:02:21,608 --> 00:02:24,809
The objective isn't to automate
architecture.

41
00:02:24,809 --> 00:02:27,534
It's to augment the architect.

42
00:02:27,534 --> 00:02:31,269
And that leads to another important part
of Articulate.

43
00:02:31,269 --> 00:02:32,740
Conversation.

44
00:02:32,740 --> 00:02:36,090
Architects spend a lot of time asking
questions.

45
00:02:36,090 --> 00:02:38,287
Why was this decision made?

46
00:02:38,287 --> 00:02:40,484
What depends on this system?

47
00:02:40,484 --> 00:02:43,450
What happens if we change this service?

48
00:02:43,450 --> 00:02:46,801
Have we solved this problem somewhere else
before?

49
00:02:46,801 --> 00:02:50,920
Today, answering those questions often
means searching through documents,
diagrams,

50
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:53,502
repositories and speaking to different
people.

51
00:02:53,502 --> 00:02:57,621
If architectural knowledge can be
represented in a form that

52
00:02:57,621 --> 00:03:01,741
AI can reason about, then conversation
becomes a natural way

53
00:03:01,741 --> 00:03:03,211
of exploring it.

54
00:03:03,211 --> 00:03:07,331
I should be able to ask Articulate a
question about

55
00:03:07,331 --> 00:03:11,450
the architecture and have it gather the
relevant knowledge, understand

56
00:03:11,450 --> 00:03:15,185
the relationships and help me reason about
the answer.

57
00:03:15,185 --> 00:03:16,998
Conversation isn't the architecture.

58
00:03:16,998 --> 00:03:19,579
And it isn't the knowledge model.

59
00:03:19,579 --> 00:03:23,698
It's the interface through which I
collaborate with the system.

60
00:03:23,698 --> 00:03:28,821
Behind that conversation is a continuously
evolving model of the architecture.

61
00:03:28,821 --> 00:03:30,494
Discovery contributes knowledge.

62
00:03:30,494 --> 00:03:32,555
Architecture decisions contribute
knowledge.

63
00:03:32,555 --> 00:03:34,617
Solution designs contribute knowledge.

64
00:03:34,617 --> 00:03:38,865
So do source code, infrastructure and
eventually operational information.

65
00:03:38,865 --> 00:03:43,551
None of those sources necessarily tells us
the complete truth

66
00:03:43,551 --> 00:03:45,223
on its own.

67
00:03:45,223 --> 00:03:47,285
Instead, they provide evidence.

68
00:03:47,285 --> 00:03:52,845
As new evidence becomes available, our
understanding of the architecture can
evolve.

69
00:03:52,845 --> 00:03:56,656
That means the model is never really
finished.

70
00:03:56,656 --> 00:04:01,778
And I think that's a much more realistic
representation of architecture.

71
00:04:01,778 --> 00:04:06,464
Architecture isn't something we document
once and then periodically update.

72
00:04:06,464 --> 00:04:09,837
It's something we are continuously
learning about.

73
00:04:09,837 --> 00:04:13,883
This idea leads to a number of
capabilities that I

74
00:04:13,883 --> 00:04:16,418
want to explore throughout the project.

75
00:04:16,418 --> 00:04:20,086
Articulate needs to discover architectural
knowledge from different sources.

76
00:04:20,086 --> 00:04:24,132
It needs to preserve that knowledge and
understand how it

77
00:04:24,132 --> 00:04:25,576
changes over time.

78
00:04:25,576 --> 00:04:29,622
It needs to let architects explore what is
known through

79
00:04:29,622 --> 00:04:31,066
conversation and visualisation.

80
00:04:31,066 --> 00:04:35,112
It should help us reason about the impact
of change.

81
00:04:35,112 --> 00:04:39,158
It should support the solution design
process by challenging assumptions,

82
00:04:39,158 --> 00:04:42,448
identifying constraints and preserving the
reasoning behind decisions.

83
00:04:42,448 --> 00:04:46,494
And it should help us understand what
capabilities and solutions

84
00:04:46,494 --> 00:04:49,406
already exist before we create something
new.

85
00:04:49,406 --> 00:04:53,074
These aren't intended to be a fixed
feature list.

86
00:04:53,074 --> 00:04:57,498
They are architectural capabilities that
will evolve as the project evolves.

87
00:04:57,498 --> 00:05:01,543
And importantly, I don't yet know exactly
what all of

88
00:05:01,543 --> 00:05:03,323
them will look like.

89
00:05:03,323 --> 00:05:07,369
That's part of what this journal is here
to discover.

90
00:05:07,369 --> 00:05:12,119
All of this brings me back to the phrase I

91
00:05:12,119 --> 00:05:14,209
used at the beginning.

92
00:05:14,209 --> 00:05:15,905
Architectural intelligence.

93
00:05:15,905 --> 00:05:20,655
For me, architectural intelligence is the
ability to understand architecture,

94
00:05:20,655 --> 00:05:25,405
preserve what we know about it, reason
about relationships and

95
00:05:25,405 --> 00:05:28,825
decisions, and explore the consequences of
change.

96
00:05:28,825 --> 00:05:32,688
That is the idea Articulate is ultimately
exploring.

97
00:05:32,688 --> 00:05:37,438
Can we build systems that don't simply
store architecture documentation,

98
00:05:37,438 --> 00:05:40,858
but actually help us reason about
architecture?

99
00:05:40,858 --> 00:05:46,052
Can AI work alongside architects without
attempting to replace their judgement?

100
00:05:46,052 --> 00:05:50,802
And can architectural knowledge become
something that continuously evolves rather

101
00:05:50,802 --> 00:05:54,222
than something we periodically try to
document?

102
00:05:54,222 --> 00:05:58,085
I don't know all of the answers yet.

103
00:05:58,085 --> 00:06:02,835
And I expect some of the ideas behind
Articulate to

104
00:06:02,835 --> 00:06:05,812
change considerably as I build it.

105
00:06:05,812 --> 00:06:09,232
That's really the point of the project.

106
00:06:09,232 --> 00:06:10,933
So, what is Articulate?

107
00:06:10,933 --> 00:06:14,798
At this point in the journey, I would
describe it

108
00:06:14,798 --> 00:06:17,220
as an exploration into architectural
intelligence.

109
00:06:17,220 --> 00:06:21,086
An AI-native platform designed to help
architects understand, evolve and

110
00:06:21,086 --> 00:06:23,148
reason about complex software systems.

111
00:06:23,148 --> 00:06:27,735
The next step is to start turning that
ambition into an architecture.

112
00:06:27,735 --> 00:06:31,600
And that means understanding the
principles, requirements and constraints
that

113
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:35,466
should shape the system before making
decisions about how to

114
00:06:35,466 --> 00:06:36,846
build it.
